> The tangy-savory balsamic mushroom sauce that cascades over juicy beef tenderloin makes this
> meal something extra-special! Their spin is beautifully balanced and lightly sweet with
> bright acidity, plus a touch of heat from red pepper jam. Pile those creamy potatoes on the side,
> add a sprinkle of scallion greens for a fresh crunch and pop of color, and you're in for a
> sumptuously satisfying dinner adventure.

Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces.

Place potatoes in a #medium pot{} with enough salted water to cover by 2 inches. Bring to a boil
and cook until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Reserve ½ cup potato cooking liquid, then drain.
Return potatoes to #pot; cover to keep warm.

While potatoes cook, trim and thinly slice @button mushrooms{4%ounce}(trimmed and thinly sliced).
Skip slicing if your mushrooms are pre-sliced! Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(trimmed and
thinly sliced, whites and greens separated).

Pat @beef tenderloin filets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add beef and
cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} and tent with #foil{} to keep warm. Wipe out pan.

> Swap in chicken or pork for beef; cook chicken until cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side,
> or cook pork to desired doneness, 4-7 minutes per side.

To #pot with potatoes, add half the @sour cream{3%tablespoon} and @butter{1/2%tablespoon}
(1 TBSP for 4 servings); mash until smooth with a #potato masher{}, adding splashes of reserved
potato cooking liquid as needed.

Heat a drizzle of oil in #pan used for beef{} over medium heat. Add mushrooms and scallion
whites; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and slightly crispy, ~{5-7%minutes}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add @balsamic vinegar{5%teaspoon}, @red pepper jam{1%unit}, remaining sour cream, and
@sugar{1%teaspoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings); cook, stirring, until mushrooms are coated and
sauce has thickened slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> If sauce seems too thick, stir in water 1 TBSP at a time.

> Use pan used for chicken or pork here.

Slice beef crosswise.

Divide beef and mashed potatoes between plates. Spoon mushroom sauce over beef and garnish with
scallion greens. Serve.

> Slice chicken or pork against the grain.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.